A rodent herbivore reduces its predation risk through ecosystem engineering

Background

The environment plays a role in predator-prey relationships. This paper studied Brandts voles which modify their habitat by cutting down bunchgrass (Achnatherum splendens) in the presence of shrikes. A. splendens grass is unpalatable and not a vole food source. Shrikes perch on these bunchgrasses to hunt voles and also impale voles grass spikes for later consumption. By decreasing the volume of bunchgrass voles reduced visitations by shrikes leading to a drop in vole mortality rates. Their ecosystem engineering through damaging roots and clipping leaves can directly reduce their own predation risk by modifying habitat structure.


Data Description

The data set I used was deposited on Dryad. https://datadryad.org/stash/dataset/doi:10.5061/dryad.cvdncjt57
Column A-E: Data used to generate Figure 2A

Column R-X: Data used to generate Figure 4

Figure 2

Inferential Statistic + Figure Replication


Figure 2 was about observing randomly 15 pairs of randomly selected A. splendens grass bunches 15 with voles and 15 without. The paired grass bunches were at least 15 meters apart and 30 meters away from other pairs. They recorded the presence of voles and presence of birds and found that vole presence had an effect on A. splendens size and the amount of grass coverage affected how often predatory shrikes would visit.

Figure 2A

g


I summarized change in plant volume according to vole presence and made a barplot. The error bars are mean +/- the standard error. Using the inferential anova below I decided that the difference in the means was significantly different.

They found that the average plant volume of A. splendens grass, given vole presence, was reduced by 0.63 m3, whereas the average plant volume of A. splendens in the absence of voles increased by 0.49 m3, as compared to the initial conditions (F1, 14 = 15.09; p = 0.0017; Figure 2A). I tested the data using a repeated measures anova.

# Repeated measures anova change in plant volume predicted by vole presence.
model <- aov(Change_plantvol~factor(Vole_Presence)+Error(factor(Pair_number)), data = d)
summary(model)
## 
## Error: factor(Pair_number)
##           Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)

## Error: Within
##                       Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value  Pr(>F)   
## factor(Vole_Presence)  1  9.498   9.498   15.09 0.00165 **
## Residuals             14  8.813   0.629                   
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

I chose a repeated measures anova because I wanted to see if there was a significant difference in the change in plant volume of each paired group. I found the same F and p values with a significance of 0.01. The authors didnt say what type of test was used to get their statistical results. I had tried a one way anova and gotten values that were close but double the degrees of freedom.

Figure 2B was about plotting the relationship between plant coverage and visits by predatory birds. There is a positive correlation between the two variables which makes sense since more plant coverage = more hunting perches for the birds.

The paper reports: The total number of visits by predatory birds per plot was positively correlated with the coverage of A. splendens grass (pseudo-R2 = 0.252; z-ratio = 2.185; p = 0.029; Figure 2B).

# Generalized Linear Model
glm <- glm(data = d, Birds_total15 ~ Plant_cover, family= "poisson")
summary(glm)
##

with(summary(glm), 1 - deviance/null.deviance)
## [1] 0.2519348


I chose to do a generalized linear model because the number of visits is a discrete variable. I got a z value of 2.185 and a p value 0.0289 which match with reported data. I then calculated McFaddens R-squared which turned out to be 0.2519348 matching the reported psudo-R2

Figure 3

Summary Statistics


Figure 3 was a Semi-natural manipulative experiment to study how the predation risk affected vole activity. They fenced off 12 plots so shrikes could not attack the voles and had 12 plots open to the air. In half of each set they placed a pair of subadult voles. In total there were 6 replicates of each condition. The only two significant findings were that birds more frequently visited plots with voles if not fenced off and that voles significantly decreased plant volume in the presence of birds.


I worked really hard on this and didnt want to delete the whole thing even though the graphs are not what I wanted. The tables accurately report the mean, SD, SE of each variable that I made throught the tidyverse. The graphs are supposed to be barcharts reporting the mean and error bars for the standard error of the mean. I was unable to make bars sorted by both predator presence and rodent presence. In the end I was able to make a boxplot which show the median and quantiles of the data which are sorted by both predator presence and rodent presence. This shows some similar trends but the graphs are not the same as the paper.

Figure 4

Descriptive Statistic


Figure 4 was a semi-natural manipulative experiment to study the effects of grass coverage on bird and vole behavior. Four voles were placed in each plot and recaptured at then end of the experiment to calculate mortality. The A. splendens grass was transplanted into buckets so the voles are unable to damage them. The differing amounts of grass coverage didnt affect total bird visits per plot 4A but did significantly affect vole feeding behavior 4B and vole mortality 4C.

Figure 4A

We see a significant difference in vole mortality rates across the differing amounts of grass coverage. With only 4 voles per plot the only mortality options are 0, 25, 50 or 100%.

Conclusions

This was a very interesting paper to read because we usually hear more about animals adapting to their environments and less about animals adapting their environment to avoid predators. It was a bit hard to figure out what statistical tests I need to run for the figures but it ended up fine. I learned a lot about sorting and sectioning data as well as different graphing functions.
